Q: "Here comes a perfectly valid argument: First, being an ingredient of Dry Fast Topcoat is sufficient for not being an ingredient of Eye Definer. Second, every ingredient of Dry Fast Topcoat is an ingredient of Hair Glaze or an ingredient of Golden Egg or an ingredient of Eye Definer. Third, being an ingredient of Dry Fast Topcoat is sufficient for not being an ingredient of Hair Glaze. From this follows: Being an ingredient of Dry Fast Topcoat is sufficient for being an ingredient of Golden Egg."
 Is the argument, given the explicitly stated premises, deductively valid or invalid?
A:

Q: "Is Fred a cousin of Robert? Is Joe related to Bob? In large families, it is sometimes difficult to keep track of all one's relatives. The following argument seeks to clarify some such relations: First premise: It is false that Fred is a half-brother of Clinton. Second premise: No half-brother of Harry and no schoolmate of Douglas is a half-brother of Clinton. We may conclude that Fred is a schoolmate of Douglas or a half-brother of Harry."
 Is the argument, given the explicitly stated premises, deductively valid or invalid?
A:

Q: "Here comes a perfectly valid argument: First of all, no workmate of Patty is an aunt of Elsie. Hence, nobody is neither an aunt of Elsie nor a workmate of Patty."
 Is the argument, given the explicitly stated premises, deductively valid or invalid?
A:

Q: "Here comes a perfectly valid argument: Oliver is an admirer of FC Internazionale Milano or a supporter of FC Olimpik Donetsk. A:

Q: "It is not always easy to see who is related to whom -- and in which ways. The following argument pertains to this question: First of all, nobody is neither an uncle of Ward nor an uncle of Rene. Next, whoever is not a grandson of Jeffrey is not both an uncle of Rene and a stepbrother of Benny. Plus,being a stepbrother of Benny is necessary for not being an uncle of Ward. Therefore, whoever is not an uncle of Ward is a grandson of Jeffrey."
 Is the argument, given the explicitly stated premises, deductively valid or invalid?
A:
